posts.name: joel truher
posts.cooked:
Hi everybody,

A little while ago, team 100 stumbled on navx issue 69 , which is that getRate() is completely broken, and has been broken for years.  Poking around github, it seems like the last time any issue was closed was over a year ago, and the last time a PR was merged was three years ago.

So … this kinda smells like abandonware?

Does anyone know what the deal is with Kauai and the NavX platform and/or code?

Maybe there should be a user fork?

@aeastet @slibert are you still around?

posts.name: James Taylor
posts.cooked:
I can investigate. That repo was for generation 1 navx, which is no longer in development. It should have been fixed in generation 2, but I will verify.

We don’t monitor Kauailabs GitHub. The support site crashes frequently, and about 99% of the time, it does not alert us to tickets. We are working on a new support solution.  We currently ask that all support be asked by emailing support_ca@studica.com .

posts.name: joel truher
posts.cooked:
Hey everybody, just circling back on this issue, which we never really resolved during the build season.

Yesterday, one of our students discovered that getRawGyroZ(), always returns zero – no wonder our velocity controller didn’t work.  Further investigation seems to indicate that the USB interface is only capable of passing “processed” or “raw” data but not both, and of course we want the “processed” theta, but (because of bug 69) the “raw” omega.

So there appears to be no way to get theta and omega from the NavX micro.  Am I reading the situation wrong?  Is there some way to get both “processed” and “raw” data over USB?

Incidentally, the NavX-MXP does provide both theta and omega, apparently because SPI can do it?

posts.cooked:
Indeed.

Was there something you wanted to say about that doc?

Or were you just concurring that, indeed, navx-MXP supports SPI, avoiding the issues with USB (no raw data) and i2c (roborio explodes)?
